<DOC><DOCNO> AP900409-0228 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-90 1428EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0022 04-09 0204</FIRST><SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0022,0210</SECOND><HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD><NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closingindices; No pickup</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Shares closed modestly higher Monday on London'sStock Exchange after the market spent the day drifting lazilyupward.   Dealers said investors were sticking to the sidelines on thefirst full day of a new trading account and as the long Easterholiday weekend approached.   The exchange divides trading into two-week and three-weektrading periods for accounting purposes.   ``It's going to be a quiet week, I'm afraid,'' one Britishequities dealer said.   A sharp rebound in Tokyo earlier Monday and a relatively steadyWall Street bolstered the London market, dealers said. They alsocited a shortage of some stocks.   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 6.6points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 2,227.7.   The index finished just below its session high of 2,227.9, whichit posted in the first hour of trading. The index's session low was2,218.8.   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 2.1 points at 1,742.3at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 3.03 pointsto close at 1,203.38.   Volume was a modest 304.6 million shares, down from 578.6million on Friday.</TEXT></DOC>